Models¶

class experimenteditor.models.Experiment¶
exp_pk¶

The primary key of the experiment. Using pk or id in any experiment query will fail. Use exp_pk instead.

experiment_title¶

The title of the experiment.

experiment_created_date¶

A Python datetime that is set upon filling out a title and hitting the “Create” button. Also applies to duplicated experiments.

created_by¶

A reference to a django.contrib.auth.models.User instance that indicates who created an experiment. This determines what users can see on the “My Experiments” page.

is_scheduled¶

A boolean that is true from the time a user schedules an experiment to the time it ends and is done processing. Is used to disable some functions of the “My Experiments” page.

has_results()¶
Returns:Whether or not the experiment has associated logs/plots. Controls whether or not the “View Results” page is available from the “My Experiments” page.
Return type:bool
get_results()¶
Returns:A QuerySet of ObservableQuantity objects that are currently associated with the experiment.
Return type:QuerySet
get_results_url()¶
Returns:An absolute url to the experiment’s “View Results” page.
Return type:string
slugify_name()¶
Returns:A CamelCase version of the title concatenated with the primary key of the experiment. Used in experimenteditor.tasks.send_experiment_json().
Return type:string
has_end()¶
Returns:True if the experiment can be scheduled due to it ending, False if it can’t.
Return type:bool
get_all_commands_list()¶
Returns:A list of every command that is associated with the experiment.
Return type:list of Command objects
class experimenteditor.models.Command¶
parent_experiment¶

References the experiment that the command is in.

delay¶

A Python Decimal object that supports numbers up to 99999.999999. In practice, this will be 14400 (4 hours in seconds) or below (but not negative). This sets when the command goes off, in seconds, relative to the start of the experiment.

class experimenteditor.models.OneTimeSSSCommand(experimenteditor.models.Command)¶
command_choice¶

A django.db.models.ChoiceField that internally stores what command they would like to execute and externally displays that command and what units the arguments are in (see quantity)

quantity¶

A experimenteditor.models.SeperatedValuesField that takes a comma-seperated list of values from the frontend. Normalizes to a Python list of strings. Is validated for number of arguments in experimenteditor/forms.py on command creation/edit.

is_repeated¶

Deprecated, along with repeat_delay and repeat_count due to looping issues.

class experimenteditor.models.CANCommand(experimenteditor.models.Command)¶
length¶

A ChoiceField that specifies the message length (from 0-8 bytes).

message¶

The hexidecimal message string to be sent to the specified ID. Due to the javascript in the CANCommand form, cannot be longer than 2 times the length (in characters).

message_id¶

The hexidecimal id string. Is only 8 characters long, no more, no less.

interface¶

The interface (currently only can1 since we don’t know whether or not can0 will be useful) the message is sent to. Stored as an integer (1, in this case).

is_extended_can¶

A boolean that determines if the message is extended CAN or not. The setting of the first bit is taken care of by the experimenteditor.tasks.send_experiment_json() task at send time.

class experimenteditor.models.CANGenCommand(experimenteditor.models.Command)¶
interface¶

See CANCommand.interface.

gap¶

The gap (in ms) between consecutive generated messages. 200 ms if left blank, can be 0 for ASAP message explosions.

generate_extended_can¶

See CANCommand.is_extended_can.

send_rtr_frame¶

Boolean. If you figure out what this is, add it to the docs.

message_length¶

0-8, blank for random, or ‘i’ for increasing.

message_id¶

See CANCommand.message_id, except can be left blank or set to “i” for increasing.

can_data¶

0-8 hex bytes, “i” for increasing, or leave blank for random data.

number_of_can_frames_before_end¶

Specifies the number of CAN frames (sent? sent+received? just received?) before this CanGEN command terminates.

class experimenteditor.models.ObservableQuantity¶
related_experiment¶

Contains a reference to the Experiment this plot is associated with.

related_run¶

Contains a reference to the RunResult this plot is associated with.

xdata¶

A SeperatedValuesField that contains all the x coordinates/timestamps. Normalizes to a Python list of strings, so be sure to cast each element to a float before doing anything numeric.

ydata¶

A SeperatedValuesField that contains all the y coordinates of the scatter plot. Right now can only visualize axle-based wheel speed in mph, so is guaranteed to be that. Also normalizes to a list of strings.

entry¶

A reference to an SPNPGNEntry that specifies what SPN/PGN the plot is representing.

related_run

Specifies what RunResult object this observable quantity is bound to. Is None on first creation through the “Visualize” page, but is assigned later on experiment schedule.

gen_plot_html()¶

Generates a plotly html div as a string to be used in a template. Use the Django safe filter when displaying results of this method in templates.

Returns:A string that contains div HTML to render a plot using plotly.js.
class experimenteditor.models.RunResult¶
experiment¶

Contains a reference to the Experiment this plot/log set is associated with.

event¶

Contains a reference to the associated schedule.models.Event. This is used to get when the RunResult was created.

log¶

Contains the log for this experiment run, as a string.
